"Zavaleta E.S., Thomas B.D., Chiariello N.R., Asner G.P., Shaw M.R., Field C.B.","Plants reverse warming effect on ecosystem water balance",2003,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","100","17",,"9892","9893",,,10.1073/pnas.1732012100,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0043193965&partnerID=40&md5=57a8ffa2d026b0a02d6f3e165ac88a0a","Department of Biological Sciences, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Jasper Ridge Biological Preserve, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Carnegie Institution of Washington, 260 Panama Street, Stanford, CA 94305, United States","Zavaleta, E.S., Department of Biological Sciences, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States, Carnegie Institution of Washington, 260 Panama Street, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Thomas, B.D., Department of Biological Sciences, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Chiariello, N.R., Jasper Ridge Biological Preserve, Stanford University, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Asner, G.P., Carnegie Institution of Washington, 260 Panama Street, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Shaw, M.R., Carnegie Institution of Washington, 260 Panama Street, Stanford, CA 94305, United States; Field, C.B., Carnegie Institution of Washington, 260 Panama Street, Stanford, CA 94305, United States","Models predict that global warming may increase aridity in water-limited ecosystems by accelerating evapotranspiration. We show that interactions between warming and the dominant biota in a grassland ecosystem produced the reverse effect. In a 2-year field experiment, simulated warming increased spring soil moisture by 5-10% under both ambient and elevated CO2. Warming also accelerated the decline of canopy greenness (normalized difference vegetation index) each spring by 11-17% by inducing earlier plant senescence. Lower transpirational water losses resulting from this earlier senescence provide a mechanism for the unexpected rise in soil moisture. Our findings illustrate the potential for organism-environment interactions to modify the direction as well as the magnitude of global change effects on ecosystem functioning.",,"carbon dioxide; article; ecosystem; evapotranspiration; fluid balance; grassland; greenhouse effect; plant; priority journal; senescence; soil moisture; spring; warming; water loss; Carbon Dioxide; Ecosystem; Greenhouse Effect; Plants; Soil; Temperature; Water; Water Supply; cellular organisms",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Soil; Water, 7732-18-5",,,,"Gregory, J.M., Mitchell, J.F.B., Brady, A.J., (1997) J. Climate, 10, pp. 662-686; Manabe, S., Wetherald, R.T., (1986) Science, 232, pp. 626-628; Rind, D., (1988) J. Geophys. Res., 93, pp. 5385-5412; Valdes, J.B., Seoane, R.S., North, G.R., (1994) J. Hydrol., 161, pp. 389-413; Gleick, P.H., (1989) Rev. Geophys., 27, pp. 329-344; Komescu, A.U., Eikan, A., Oz, S., (1998) Climatic Change, 40, pp. 519-545; Dickinson, R.E., (1995) Remote Sensing Environ., 51, pp. 27-38; Kleidon, A., Heimann, M., (1999) Global Ecol. Biogeogr. Lett., 8, pp. 397-405; Schulze, E.-D., Kelliher, F.M., Körner, C., Lloyd, J., Leuning, R., (1994) Annu. Rev. Ecol. System, 25, pp. 629-660; Chapin, F.S., Shaver, G.R., Giblin, A.E., Nadelhoffer, K.J., Laundre, J.A., (1995) Ecology, 76, pp. 694-711; Harte, J., Torn, M.S., Chang, F.R., Feifarek, B., Kinzig, A.P., Shaw, R., Shen, K., (1995) Ecol. Appl., 5, pp. 132-150; Yonghui, Y., Zhiping, W., Sakura, Y., Changyuan, T., Shindo, S., (2002) Yingyong Shengtai Xuebao, 13, pp. 667-671; Miglietta, F., Giuntoli, A., Bindi, M., (1996) Photosynth. Res., 47, pp. 281-290; Topp, G.C., Davis, J.L., Annan, A.P., (1980) Water Resourc. Res., 16, pp. 574-582; Price, M.V., Waser, N.M., (1998) Ecology, 79, pp. 1261-1270; Alatalo, J.M., Totland, O., (1997) Global Change Biol., 3, pp. 74-79; Roche, C.T., Thill, D.C., Shafii, B., (1997) Weed Sci., 45, pp. 763-770; Sandvik, S